   120→**Key rules:**
   121→- Import `atom` from `'nanostores'` (NOT `@nanostores/core` or any other path)
   122→- Import types using `import type` syntax
   123→- Use relative path `'../types'` (stores are in `src/lib/stores/`, types is at `src/lib/types.ts`)
   124→- Always use explicit generic on `atom<T>()` -- never let TypeScript infer the type
   125→- `null` initial value for stores that have no data yet (price, market); empty array for chart; `'connecting'` as meaningful default for status
   126→- One store per file, one export per file
   127→- No barrel file (`stores/index.ts`) -- consumers import directly from each store file
   128→
   129→### Format Utilities -- Exact Code
   130→
   131→**File: `src/lib/utils/format-utils.ts`**
   132→
   133→```typescript
   134→/**
   135→ * Format a price as USD with 2 decimal places.
   136→ * Example: 68432.17 → "$68,432.17"
   137→ */
   138→export function formatPrice(price: number): string {
   139→  return new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', {
   140→    style: 'currency',
   141→    currency: 'USD',
   142→    minimumFractionDigits: 2,
   143→    maximumFractionDigits: 2,
   144→  }).format(price);
   145→}
   146→
   147→/**
   148→ * Format a percentage with sign and 1 decimal place.
   149→ * Example: 2.3 → "+2.3%", -1.8 → "-1.8%"
   150→ */
   151→export function formatPercent(value: number): string {
   152→  return new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', {
   153→    style: 'percent',
   154→    minimumFractionDigits: 1,
   155→    maximumFractionDigits: 1,
   156→    signDisplay: 'always',
   157→  }).format(value / 100);
   158→}
   159→
   160→/**
   161→ * Format an absolute USD change with sign.
   162→ * Example: 1534.22 → "+$1,534.22", -892.40 → "-$892.40"
   163→ */
   164→export function formatAbsoluteChange(value: number): string {
   165→  return new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', {
   166→    style: 'currency',
   167→    currency: 'USD',
   168→    minimumFractionDigits: 2,
   169→    maximumFractionDigits: 2,
   170→    signDisplay: 'always',
   171→  }).format(value);
   172→}
   173→
   174→/**
   175→ * Format market cap with compact notation.
   176→ * Example: 1340000000000 → "$1.34T", 892450000000 → "$892.45B"
   177→ */
   178→export function formatMarketCap(value: number): string {
   179→  return new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', {
   180→    style: 'currency',
   181→    currency: 'USD',
   182→    notation: 'compact',
   183→    minimumFractionDigits: 2,
   184→    maximumFractionDigits: 2,
   185→  }).format(value);
   186→}
   187→
   188→/**
   189→ * Format a price range with compact notation.
   190→ * Example: (66900, 68900) → "$66.9K — $68.9K"
   191→ *
   192→ * Note: Intl.NumberFormat compact notation capitalizes the suffix (K, M, B, T).
   193→ * The architecture spec shows lowercase "k" but Intl produces uppercase "K".
   194→ * Using Intl output as-is to avoid manual string manipulation (per AC #7).
   195→ */
   196→export function formatRange(low: number, high: number): string {
   197→  const formatter = new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', {
   198→    style: 'currency',
   199→    currency: 'USD',
   200→    notation: 'compact',
   201→    minimumFractionDigits: 1,
   202→    maximumFractionDigits: 1,
   203→  });
   204→  return `${formatter.format(low)} — ${formatter.format(high)}`;
   205→}
   206→
   207→/**
   208→ * Format a chart tooltip with price and time.
   209→ * Example: (68432.17, 1711972200000) → "$68,432.17 at 14:30"
   210→ */
   211→export function formatChartTooltip(price: number, timestamp: number): string {
   212→  const formattedPrice = formatPrice(price);
   213→  const formattedTime = new Intl.DateTimeFormat('en-US', {
   214→    hour: '2-digit',
   215→    minute: '2-digit',
   216→    hour12: false,
   217→  }).format(new Date(timestamp));
   218→  return `${formattedPrice} at ${formattedTime}`;
   219→}
   220→```
   221→
   222→**Implementation notes:**
   223→- `formatPercent` divides by 100 because `Intl.NumberFormat` with `style: 'percent'` multiplies the input by 100. The input `value` is already a percentage (e.g., `2.3` means 2.3%), so divide by 100 to get the correct output.
   224→- `formatRange` uses em dash ` — ` as separator per UX spec.
   225→- `formatChartTooltip` uses 24-hour time format with `hour12: false` per UX spec ("14:30").
   226→- All functions are pure -- no side effects, no store access, no DOM interaction.
   227→- Each function creates a new `Intl.NumberFormat` instance. For v1, this is acceptable. If profiling shows hot paths, instances can be cached at module scope later.
   228→
   229→### Test File -- Exact Code
   230→
   231→**File: `src/lib/utils/format-utils.test.ts`**
   232→
   233→```typescript
   234→import { describe, it, expect } from 'vitest';
   235→import {
   236→  formatPrice,
   237→  formatPercent,
   238→  formatAbsoluteChange,
   239→  formatMarketCap,
   240→  formatRange,
   241→  formatChartTooltip,
   242→} from './format-utils';
   243→
   244→describe('formatPrice', () => {
   245→  it('formats a normal price', () => {
   246→    expect(formatPrice(68432.17)).toBe('$68,432.17');
   247→  });
   248→
   249→  it('formats zero', () => {
   250→    expect(formatPrice(0)).toBe('$0.00');
   251→  });
   252→
   253→  it('formats a large price', () => {
   254→    expect(formatPrice(100000)).toBe('$100,000.00');
   255→  });
   256→
   257→  it('formats a small decimal', () => {
   258→    expect(formatPrice(0.5)).toBe('$0.50');
   259→  });
   260→
   261→  it('handles NaN', () => {
   262→    expect(formatPrice(NaN)).toBe('NaN');
   263→  });
   264→});
   265→
   266→describe('formatPercent', () => {
   267→  it('formats a positive percentage', () => {
   268→    expect(formatPercent(2.3)).toBe('+2.3%');
   269→  });
   270→
   271→  it('formats a negative percentage', () => {
   272→    expect(formatPercent(-1.8)).toBe('-1.8%');
   273→  });
   274→
   275→  it('formats zero', () => {
   276→    // Intl may format zero as "+0.0%" or "0.0%" depending on signDisplay behavior
   277→    const result = formatPercent(0);
   278→    expect(result).toMatch(/0\.0%/);
   279→  });
   280→
   281→  it('formats a large percentage', () => {
   282→    expect(formatPercent(15.7)).toBe('+15.7%');
   283→  });
   284→});
   285→
   286→describe('formatAbsoluteChange', () => {
   287→  it('formats a positive change', () => {
   288→    expect(formatAbsoluteChange(1534.22)).toBe('+$1,534.22');
   289→  });
   290→
   291→  it('formats a negative change', () => {
   292→    expect(formatAbsoluteChange(-892.4)).toBe('-$892.40');
   293→  });
   294→
   295→  it('formats zero', () => {
   296→    const result = formatAbsoluteChange(0);
   297→    expect(result).toMatch(/\$0\.00/);
   298→  });
   299→});
   300→
   301→describe('formatMarketCap', () => {
   302→  it('formats trillions', () => {
   303→    expect(formatMarketCap(1340000000000)).toBe('$1.34T');
   304→  });
   305→
   306→  it('formats billions', () => {
   307→    expect(formatMarketCap(892450000000)).toBe('$892.45B');
   308→  });
   309→
   310→  it('formats millions', () => {
   311→    expect(formatMarketCap(5670000)).toBe('$5.67M');
   312→  });
   313→
   314→  it('formats zero', () => {
   315→    expect(formatMarketCap(0)).toBe('$0.00');
   316→  });
   317→});
   318→
   319→describe('formatRange', () => {
   320→  it('formats a normal range', () => {
   321→    const result = formatRange(66900, 68900);
   322→    // Intl compact notation uses uppercase K
   323→    expect(result).toContain('—');
   324→    expect(result).toMatch(/\$66\.9K?\s*—\s*\$68\.9K?/i);
   325→  });
   326→
   327→  it('formats equal values', () => {
   328→    const result = formatRange(68000, 68000);
   329→    expect(result).toContain('—');
   330→  });
   331→});
   332→
   333→describe('formatChartTooltip', () => {
   334→  it('formats price and time', () => {
   335→    // Create a known timestamp: 14:30 UTC
   336→    const date = new Date('2024-04-01T14:30:00Z');
   337→    const result = formatChartTooltip(68432.17, date.getTime());
   338→    expect(result).toContain('$68,432.17');
   339→    expect(result).toContain('at');
   340→    // Time will vary by timezone in test environment, so just check format
   341→    expect(result).toMatch(/\$68,432\.17 at \d{2}:\d{2}/);
   342→  });
   343→});
   344→```
   345→
   346→**Test notes:**
   347→- The NaN test for `formatPrice` checks that it returns the string `'NaN'` -- this is `Intl.NumberFormat`'s default behavior. The dev agent should verify this in the Node.js version being used and adjust the assertion if needed.
   348→- The zero-with-sign tests use `toMatch` rather than exact equality because `signDisplay: 'always'` behavior for zero can vary between JS engines (may produce `+$0.00` or `$0.00`).
   349→- The `formatRange` test uses a case-insensitive regex because compact notation suffix casing may differ.
   350→- The `formatChartTooltip` time test is timezone-aware: the displayed time depends on the local timezone of the test runner. The regex pattern `\d{2}:\d{2}` validates the format without asserting a specific time.
   351→
   352→### Import Patterns
   353→
   354→Components and services will import stores and formatters as follows (for reference in future stories):
   355→
   356→```typescript
   357→// Store imports (from a component or service)
   358→import { priceStore } from '../lib/stores/price-store';
   359→import { statusStore } from '../lib/stores/status-store';
   360→import { marketStore } from '../lib/stores/market-store';
   361→import { chartStore } from '../lib/stores/chart-store';
   362→
   363→// Formatter imports (from a component)
   364→import { formatPrice, formatPercent, formatAbsoluteChange } from '../lib/utils/format-utils';
   365→
   366→// Type imports
   367→import type { PriceTick } from '../lib/types';
   368→```
   369→
   370→### Anti-Patterns (DO NOT)
   371→
   372→- **No barrel files** -- do NOT create `src/lib/stores/index.ts` or `src/lib/utils/index.ts`. Import directly from each module.
   373→- **No setInterval** -- not relevant to this story, but never use it in the project. Use recursive `setTimeout` for polling.
   374→- **No store writes from components** -- stores are written to ONLY by services (Story 2.2+). This story only creates stores; writing happens in later stories.
   375→- **No manual string formatting** -- never use `toFixed()`, string concatenation, or template literals to format numbers for display. Always use `Intl.NumberFormat`.
   376→- **No derived data in stores** -- do not store formatted strings. Stores hold raw numbers; formatting happens at the component level via `format-utils.ts`.
   377→- **No default objects as initial store values** -- use `null` for "no data yet" (not `{ price: 0, timestamp: 0, direction: 'neutral' }`).
   378→
   379→### Previous Story Intelligence
   380→
   381→From Story 1.1 (done):
   382→- Project uses Astro 6.0.8, Node 25.8.1, TypeScript strict mode
   383→- `nanostores` v1.2.0 is installed as a production dependency (verified in `package.json`)
   384→- Directory structure already exists: `src/lib/stores/`, `src/lib/utils/` (created with `.gitkeep` files)
   385→- `src/lib/types.ts` already defines all four interfaces: `PriceTick`, `MarketData`, `ChartPoint`, `ConnectionStatus`
   386→- Vitest v4.1.1 configured, `npm run test` runs tests matching `src/**/*.test.ts`
   387→- ESLint and Prettier are configured
   388→- `ConnectionStatus` is exported as a `type` alias (not `interface`) -- this is acceptable per Story 1.1 review
   389→
   390→Deferred items from Story 1.1 review relevant to this story:
   391→- `PriceTick.timestamp` has no unit documented -- treat as milliseconds (Unix epoch ms from `Date.now()`)
   392→- `PriceTick.price` allows non-positive/non-finite values -- formatters should handle gracefully (NaN, Infinity edge cases)
   393→- `MarketData.change24h` unit is absolute USD value (not percentage) -- `changePercent24h` is the percentage field
   394→
   395→### Files to Create
   396→
   397→| File | Type | Purpose |
   398→|---|---|---|
   399→| `src/lib/stores/price-store.ts` | New | Reactive store for current price tick |
   400→| `src/lib/stores/status-store.ts` | New | Reactive store for connection status |
   401→| `src/lib/stores/market-store.ts` | New | Reactive store for market data |
   402→| `src/lib/stores/chart-store.ts` | New | Reactive store for chart data points |
   403→| `src/lib/utils/format-utils.ts` | New | Number formatting utility functions |
   404→| `src/lib/utils/format-utils.test.ts` | New | Unit tests for all formatters |
   405→
   406→**Files NOT to modify:** No existing files need changes. The `.gitkeep` files in `stores/` and `utils/` can be removed once real files are added.
   407→
   408→### References
   409→
   410→- [Source: architecture.md#Store Patterns] -- Nano Store conventions, `atom<Type | null>(null)` pattern, explicit generics rule
   411→- [Source: architecture.md#Format Patterns] -- all formatter specifications, `Intl.NumberFormat` rule, direction indicator symbols
   412→- [Source: architecture.md#Naming Patterns] -- kebab-case for TypeScript modules, camelCase for variables/functions, `Store` suffix convention
   413→- [Source: architecture.md#Structure Patterns] -- file locations, one store per file, co-located tests
   414→- [Source: architecture.md#Enforcement Guidelines] -- anti-patterns (no barrel files, no inline formatting, no derived store data)
   415→- [Source: epics.md#Story 2.1] -- acceptance criteria
   416→- [Source: epics.md#Epic 2] -- epic context: Live Bitcoin Price Display
   417→- [Source: ux-design-specification.md#Typography] -- type scale for values (48px price, 20-24px values)
   418→- [Source: prd.md#FR1-FR5] -- price display requirements
   419→- [Source: 1-1-project-initialization-and-tooling-setup.md] -- established project patterns, installed dependencies, deferred review items
   420→
